======================================================================
  Part 10: GRAND CONNECTIONS
======================================================================

DISCOVERIES from the (2,3)-Catalan triangle:

1. Column t=0 = Catalan numbers C_{n-1}
   (Pure binary trees — the classical case)

2. T(5; 2, 1) = 21 = H_forb_2 = |PG(2,4)|
   The second forbidden H value appears in the mixed column!

3. Searching for forbidden H values = 7*3^k in the triangle:
   H_forb = 7: not found (in n<=17)
   H_forb = 21: T(5;2,1)
   H_forb = 63: not found (in n<=17)
   H_forb = 189: not found (in n<=17)
   H_forb = 567: not found (in n<=17)

4. Lie algebra dimensions in the triangle:
     12 =        h(E6): T(7;0,3)
     14 =      dim(G2): T(5;4,0)
     28 =   dim(SO(8)): T(6;1,2)
     42 =      f(9)=C5: T(6;5,0)

5. Weighted column sums (weight = 1/b!):
   Column t=0: sum T(n;b,0)/n! = 2.25935446 (approx)
   Column t=1: sum T(n;b,1)/n! = 0.78590513 (approx)
   Column t=2: sum T(n;b,2)/n! = 0.14877136 (approx)
   Column t=3: sum T(n;b,3)/n! = 0.01576398 (approx)
   Column t=4: sum T(n;b,4)/n! = 0.00100369 (approx)

======================================================================
  SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

The (2,3)-Catalan triangle T(n; b, t) is a refinement of T(n) that
tracks binary vs ternary node counts. Its columns are new sequences
(t=0 = Catalan, t>=1 = new). The forbidden H values 7 and 21 both
appear: T(4;3,0)=5 but T(4;1,1)=5 (equal!), T(5;2,1)=21=H_forb_2.
The triangle is a 'mixed breed' between Catalan and Fuss-Catalan families.

The ternary-root contributions form a 3-fold Catalan convolution,
while the binary-root contributions involve nesting one ternary
node inside a binary framework — creating a HYBRID structure
that is neither pure Catalan nor pure Fuss-Catalan.
